{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586954"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:40:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15113"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15113"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.11,0.75,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65910"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7801"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51356"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"658"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9478"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22016"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65910"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPeritonsillar abscess (quinsy) is a suppurative complication of acute bacterial tonsillitis (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about peritonsillar abscess is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Does not cause airway obstruction","Occurs in more than 50% of bacterial tonsillitis cases","Presents with deviation of uvula towards the affected side","Pus accumulates between tonsillar capsule and pharyngeal muscles","Typically resolves spontaneously without treatment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccumulation of pus between the tonsillar capsule and pharyngeal muscles\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic of peritonsillar abscess. Quinsy is relatively uncommon, with \u003Cstrong\u003Emore than 50% of bacterial tonsillitis cases\u003C/strong\u003E being an overestimate of its frequency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe abscess causes displacement of surrounding structures, with the uvula deviating \u003Cstrong\u003Eaway from the affected side\u003C/strong\u003E, not \u003Cstrong\u003Etowards it\u003C/strong\u003E. The condition requires prompt medical intervention and \u003Cstrong\u003Edoes not resolve spontaneously\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImportantly, peritonsillar abscess \u003Cstrong\u003Ecan cause airway obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E through local swelling and inflammation, making it a potentially life-threatening condition requiring urgent assessment and treatment. Other typical features include severe unilateral throat pain, trismus (difficulty opening mouth), and muffled \u0027hot potato\u0027 voice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Quinsy (peritonsillar abscess) is a serious complication of bacterial tonsillitis characterised by pus collecting between the tonsillar capsule and pharyngeal muscles","Quinsy presents with severe sore throat, trismus, muffled voice, and uvular deviation away from the affected side","Airway compromise is a potential life-threatening complication of quinsy requiring urgent intervention"],"references":["Powell J, Wilson JA. An evidence-based review of peritonsillar abscess. Clin Otolaryngol. 2012 Apr;37(2):136-45. doi: 10.1111/j.1749-4486.2012.02452.x. PMID: 22321140.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51356"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21253"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21253"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1MN4bZngAxryA6GmWBzKvAyWqsEuFH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1MN4bZngAxryA6GmWBzKvAyWqsEuFH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51356"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T13:45:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T13:45:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7801"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65910"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"